56–Deceased","1139–1234":"1139–1234","1120–Female":"1120–Deceased","1139":"1139","1256":"1256","1234":"1234","1233":"1233","1120":"1120","about 1256":"about 1256","1291":"1291","1229":"1229","Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Espanha":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain","Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain","Spain":"Spain","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Palomeque","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Spanish: habitational name from a place called Palomeque in Toledo province."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Toledo","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Luis, Jorge, Manuel, Ramon, Rafael, Juan, Antonio, Jesus, Miguel, Roberto, Carlos, Francisco.","Spanish and Jewish (Sephardic): habitational name from the city in central Spain, which was the capital of the Visigothic state between the 6th and 8th centuries. Its role declined for three centuries after the Muslim invasion of Spain, until it was taken as the capital of the kingdom of Castile between the 11th and 16th centuries. It was a major cultural and political center throughout the Middle Ages, and was also the home of an important Jewish community. The placename, first recorded in Latin as <i>Toletum</i>, is of obscure etymology, possibly connected with <i>Toleto</i> in Piedmont; Jewish tradition connects it with Hebrew <i>toledot</i> ‘generations’, but this is no more than folk etymology. Compare   Toledano  .","Jewish (Sephardic): also an adoption of the Spanish surname (see 1 above) at the moment of conversion to Roman Catholicism. After the return to Judaism (generations later), some descendants retained the surname their families used as Catholics."],"variants":[{"name":"Toledano","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Shlomo, Igal, Moshe, Shimon, Ehud, Shmuel, Yehuda.  Spanish Alberto, Gonzalo, Alina, Carlos, Conrado, Elena, Enrique, Evelia, Luis, Manuel, Miguel, Ramona.  French Gabrielle, Michel.","Spanish and Jewish (Sephardic): habitational name for someone from Toledo (see   Toledo  ), from an adjectival form of the placename."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Urraca Palomeque de Toledo was born in 1233, in Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain, her father, Caballero Gutierrez Rodriguez de Castro, was 94 and her mother, Elvira Osores, was 114. She had at least 1 son with Pedro Fernandez de Toledo Illan. She died in Spain."},"et":{"1233–":"1233–Surnud","1233–Female":"1233–Surnud","1229–Male":"1229–Surnud","1234–Male":"1234–Surnud","1256–1291":"1256–1291","1256–Male":"1256–Surnud","1139–1234":"1139–1234","1120–Female":"1120–Surnud","1139":"1139","1256":"1256","1234":"1234","1233":"1233","1120":"1120","about 1256":"umbes 1256","1291":"1291","1229":"1229","Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Espanha":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Hispaania","Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Hispaania","Spain":"Hispaania"},"fi":{"1233–":"1233–Kuollut","1233–Female":"1233–Kuollut","1229–Male":"1229–Kuollut","1234–Male":"1234–Kuollut","1256–1291":"1256–1291","1256–Male":"1256–Kuollut","1139–1234":"1139–1234","1120–Female":"1120–Kuollut","1139":"1139","1256":"1256","1234":"1234","1233":"123